{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9b540656-72a0-4c3b-95cd-243f480eb251","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** (.NET 9), which supports the modern patterns. Here's the recommended approach:\n\n**Constructor injection for `TestContext`** (MSTest v3+):\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // TestContext injected via constructor — no static property needed\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Sync per-test setup\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // sync init work\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test setup — just return Task\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await SomeAsyncWork();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via constructor (v3+). The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` static property pattern still works but is legacy.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports both `void` and `async Task`. Use **one** method; if you need both sync and async work, use the async version and do sync work there.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — also supports `async Task` for one-time class-level setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a64bfee0-0f50-49ed-90c8-3ca5d3bc90f2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended pattern for TestContext injection and initialization is:\n\n1. **TestContext**: In MSTest v3, you can inject `TestContext` via a constructor parameter or use the classic static property pattern. The modern way (MSTest 3.x) is constructor injection.\n\n2. **Sync initialization**: `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Async initialization**: `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task` return types in MSTest v3.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about the modern MSTest v3 patterns.\n\n\nSo in MSTest 3.x, I can inject TestContext directly through the constructor, and both `[TestInitialize]` and `[ClassInitialize]` support async Task methods, which gives me flexibility for async setup operations.","outputTokens":586,"requestId":"A035:4A984:186D042:1BD67B5:69FE8F13"},"id":"a49e3fdf-a2db-4544-aaa3-75b0e306e474","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:34:23.173Z","parentId":"b2557be8-7128-4e8c-b783-3247e2285e41"}
